SIMPLE: reverend
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Reverend
<hw>Rev"er*end</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧v⟦eacute⟧rend</ets>, L. <ets>reverendus</ets>, fr.
<ets>revereri</ets>. See <er>Revere</er>.]</ety> <def>Worthy of
reverence; entitled to respect mingled with fear and affection;
venerable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>reverend</qex> sire among them came.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They must give good example and <qex>reverend</qex> deportment in
the face of their children.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This word is commonly given as a title of respect to
ecclesiastics. A clergyman is styled the <xex>reverend</xex>; a dean,
the <xex>very reverend</xex>; a bishop, the <xex>right reverend</xex>;
an archbishop, the <xex>most reverend</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reverendly</ent>⟦br⟧
